<TITLE> BTCL to offer Tk 0.30/min flat NWD rate </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 21 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh Telecommunications Company Limited will offer a nationwide flat call rate of Tk 0.30 per minute to increase revenue and subscribers. A BTCL official told bdnews24.com on Thursday night after a meeting of the board that the decision, to be approved by telecoms regulator BTRC, may be effective from July 1. The board also decided to introduce free connection in Upazilas from July 1 to Sept 30, said the official with knowledge of the matter on condition that he not be named. The new tariff structure will reduce NWD call charges but hike local call cost, he added. New connection fee for Dhaka is Tk 1,000, for Chittagong Tk 500 and for other districts and Upazilas, it is fee Tk 300, with deposits of the same amounts. Under the present call rate, a client will give Tk 0.10 paisa per minute during off-peak hours and Tk 0.15 during peak hours. For NWD, peak hour call rate from one district to another is Tk 1.70 during off-peak hours. Peak hour is from 8am to 8pm. From BTCL to private land-phone operators, the tariff is Tk 0.80 during peak hours and Tk 0.70 during off-peak hours. To mobile phone, it is Tk 1 per minute in peak hours and Tk 0.70 during off-peak hours. Subscribers can talk free for some time every month. With a monthly line rent of Tk 80, a customer can have 50 minutes' bonus talk time for calls from Dhaka to Chittagong. It is 100 minutes for divisional town for the line rent of Tk 70. At Upazilas it is 100-minute free time for a line rent of Tk 50. BTCL customers get dialup internet connection without fee and an applicant is given a secret number to access internet. At present, internet use rate during off-peak is Tk 0.20 paisa and Tk 0.40 for peak hours. BTCL has 8,72,000 subscribers. The country's largest landphone operator has the capacity to serve 13 lakh users although its customer base remained almost stagnant at 8.72 lakh in the last three years. Last week, SM Khabiruzzaman, the managing director, told the media that they decided to offer Tk 0.25 per minute flat rate across the country, which was subject to approval from the BTCL board. bdn
